---
import { ArrowLeft } from "@lucide/astro";
import Icon from "../../components/Icon.astro";
import SiteFooter from "../../components/SiteFooter.astro";
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Statistics Page Redesign — Statista"
  description="Redesigning a page template used across 1M+ statistics pages, improving page structure, data visualization modularity, and integrating AI-assisted research continuations."
  canonicalPath="/work/statista-statistics"
>
  <div class="site-frame">
    <div class="site-side" aria-hidden="true"></div>
    <div class="site-page">
      <nav class="cs-nav" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <a href="/" class="cs-back">
          <Icon icon={ArrowLeft} role="inline" />
          Nikolaos Banis
        </a>
      </nav>

      <article class="cs-article">
        <header class="cs-header">
          <div class="cs-kicker">
            <span class="meta">Statista</span>
            <span class="meta cs-kicker-sep" aria-hidden="true">·</span>
            <span class="meta">2025 — Present</span>
          </div>
          <h1>Statistics Page Redesign</h1>
          <p class="cs-subtitle">
            Redesigning a page template used across 1M+ statistics pages
          </p>
        </header>

        <div class="cs-highlights">
          <p class="cs-highlights-label">What changed</p>
          <ul class="cs-highlights-list">
            <li>A clearer page structure that moves from orientation to data interpretation to next steps</li>
            <li>A modular data visualization widget that can work across surfaces and contexts</li>
            <li>Better placement of supporting text, recommendations, and source information</li>
            <li>A contextual AI side panel that helps users continue from the statistic they are viewing</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="cs-highlights-note meta">
            The first release showed positive movement in downloads per session,
            recommendation usage, and user feedback. Full rollout data pending.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="cs-body">
          <section class="cs-section">
            <h2>The problem was not more features</h2>
            <p>
              The old page had accumulated too many layers. Each addition made
              sense at the time: more context, more actions, more
              recommendations, more metadata, more product entry points. But
              together, they made the page harder to read.
            </p>
            <p>
              Users were not scrolling far enough to reach important
              recommendations. Supporting text was often truncated. Key
              information competed with secondary content. The page had become a
              collection of useful parts without a strong enough reading flow.
            </p>
            <p>
              So I started from subtraction. Instead of asking what else the
              page needed, I stripped the page back to a blank canvas and mapped
              every existing element into a clearer structure.
            </p>
            <ul class="cs-questions">
              <li>What does the user need first?</li>
              <li>What helps them trust the statistic?</li>
              <li>What helps them understand the chart?</li>
              <li>What helps them download or extract the data?</li>
              <li>What helps them continue their research?</li>
              <li>What can wait?</li>
            </ul>
            <p>That became the foundation of the redesign.</p>
          </section>

          <section class="cs-section">
            <h2>Start with orientation</h2>
            <p>
              A user arriving on a statistics page needs to understand where
              they are quickly. They need to know what the statistic is about,
              what unit it uses, what period it covers, who produced it, when it
              was updated, and whether it fits their purpose. The old page did
              not make that orientation clear enough.
            </p>
            <p>
              So the top of the page became the first major design decision. The
              header needed to carry the most important trust and relevance
              signals before the user reached the chart.
            </p>
            <ul class="cs-questions">
              <li>Title</li>
              <li>Unit</li>
              <li>Time period</li>
              <li>Publication or update context</li>
              <li>Author or source signal</li>
              <li>Topic context</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              This gave users a stronger first read of the page. Before
              interacting with the chart, they could understand the statistic,
              judge relevance, and decide whether it was useful for their work.
            </p>
            <p>That solved the first layer of the problem. But the center of the page was still the chart.</p>
          </section>

          <section class="cs-section">
            <h2>The chart needed to become a system</h2>
            <p>
              The data visualization widget was not only part of this page. It
              had to work across multiple surfaces, product contexts, and page
              structures. That changed the design problem.
            </p>
            <p>
              If the widget was designed only for the statistics page, every
              future use case would need another variation. The product would
              continue accumulating one-off solutions. So I treated the widget
              as a modular system.
            </p>
            <p>
              It needed a stable structure, but flexible parts. Information
              could be enabled, disabled, or customized depending on where the
              widget appeared. I moved the title and description to the top,
              kept support text close to the chart, placed actions at the
              bottom, and made critical information like source and context
              easier to find.
            </p>
            <p>
              The goal was to make the widget easier to understand in place,
              while making it portable enough to become a single source of truth
              across the product. That decision mattered beyond the statistics
              page — it gave the data visualization work a clearer direction for
              the new product structure.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="cs-section">
            <h2>Context had to stay close to the data</h2>
            <p>
              One issue I noticed early was that users were not scrolling enough.
              That meant important supporting information was technically
              available but practically underused.
            </p>
            <p>
              This mattered because Statista users often come to a page to
              extract a statistic and return to their own tools. Download
              behavior was one of the key signals I tracked because it reflected
              that extraction workflow. But extraction without context can be
              risky. Users still need to understand what the number means, what
              period it covers, what source it comes from, and whether there are
              important limitations.
            </p>
            <p>
              So the supporting text had to move closer to the data. The page
              needed to support quick extraction, but not at the cost of
              interpretation. This became one of the main layout principles:
              keep the chart, explanation, source, and actions connected enough
              that users do not have to assemble the meaning of the page from
              distant pieces.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="cs-section">
            <h2>Recommendations needed to become topical</h2>
            <p>
              The old page treated recommendations as something that appeared
              after the main statistic. But if users did not scroll far enough,
              those recommendations had little value.
            </p>
            <p>
              This was also connected to a broader company goal: moving away
              from separated content buckets and toward a more unified
              topic-based experience. A user looking at EV interest in Germany
              might also need related data on power generation, the battery
              market, infrastructure, policy, or key players. Those are not
              random next clicks — they are part of the same research path.
            </p>
            <p>
              So I worked with multiple teams to create space for contextual
              recommendations inside the page structure. The page became a
              shared surface where different teams could contribute to the same
              user journey: data visualization, recommendations, AI, content,
              and research. The important part was keeping one shared goal: help
              users understand the statistic and continue their research without
              feeling like they are jumping between disconnected product areas.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="cs-section">
            <h2>Research shaped the first prototype</h2>
            <p>
              The first iteration was built from previous internal research,
              existing product knowledge, and earlier findings about how users
              consume data pages.
            </p>
            <p>
              I then ran 10 qualitative sessions focused on how users read,
              understand, and use statistics pages. The sessions had two parts.
              The first part was discovery: how users consume data, what they
              look for first, how they judge relevance, and what they need to do
              next. The second part was validation: showing the prototype,
              watching reactions, collecting feedback, and understanding where
              the new structure helped or failed.
            </p>
            <p>
              This gave me both behavioral context and direct feedback on the
              proposed direction. Afterward, I synthesized the findings, aligned
              stakeholders, and moved into implementation.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="cs-section">
            <h2>The hardest part was orchestration</h2>
            <p>
              This redesign touched many teams. The page template was the
              container, but the content and product capabilities came from
              different areas: data visualization, recommendations, AI, content,
              and engineering.
            </p>
            <p>My role was to create the structure that made those parts work together. That meant defining the page logic clearly enough that every team understood where their work belonged.</p>
            <ul class="cs-questions">
              <li>What belongs in the header?</li>
              <li>What belongs inside the chart widget?</li>
              <li>What belongs near the statistic?</li>
              <li>What belongs in recommendations?</li>
              <li>What belongs in the AI side panel?</li>
              <li>What should stay out of the main flow?</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              The page had to be flexible enough to support different content
              types, but strict enough to avoid becoming another inconsistent
              legacy template.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="cs-section">
            <h2>Bringing AI into the page context</h2>
            <p>
              The AI side panel shipped with the new page experience. The goal
              was not to add AI as a separate layer on top of the page. It
              needed to work with the information the user was already viewing.
            </p>
            <p>
              The page gave the AI context. The AI gave users another way to ask
              questions, explore meaning, and move forward from the statistic.
              This fit the larger direction of the redesign: the statistics page
              should not be a dead end. It should help users understand,
              extract, and continue.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="cs-section">
            <h2>The final shift</h2>
            <p>
              The redesign changed the statistics page from a legacy content
              template into a more flexible product surface.
            </p>
            <ul class="cs-outcomes">
              <li>It improved orientation at the top of the page</li>
              <li>It made the chart widget more modular and reusable</li>
              <li>It brought supporting text closer to the data</li>
              <li>It gave recommendations better context</li>
              <li>It created space for AI without breaking the page flow</li>
              <li>It aligned multiple teams around one shared structure</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              The most important design decision was subtraction. Instead of
              adding another layer to an already crowded page, I worked backward
              from what users needed to understand first, then rebuilt the page
              around that flow.
            </p>
            <p>
              The result is a page template that can support Statista's most
              important page type today, while giving the company a stronger
              foundation for future content types, recommendations, and
              AI-assisted research.
            </p>
          </section>
        </div>
      </article>

      <SiteFooter />
    </div>
    <div class="site-side" aria-hidden="true"></div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
